Their website may just well be the worst on the internet.  My guess is it was designed in 1997.  Its slow, and the bill pay service is archaic. Good luck getting anything of substance from the site.  I have signed up for auto-pay and budget billing multiple times but it never goes into effect.  In addition, I schedule payments and they don't show on the website (although I receive emails stating the payment has been scheduled).  

But with that said, I have had no problems with their service, hence the 2 stars.







Washington Gas,
Your payment options are unbelievably torturous. Your website never works! And your telephone assistance is sub-par, repetitive, annoying, and unproductive. It takes 20 mins to make a payment if you're lucky and don't get hung up on for one mistaken number entered. Please upgrade your services.

                                                   Sincerely.
                                     At my wits end with you!







Why am I not surprised that this terrible company has 1 star?

For the past, two years since I've had WG, every few months they contact me saying they have not received payments. I then have to log on to my account and send screen shots. This is the third time it is happening. Seriously guys, maybe update your technology or get a staff has a brain. #1 reason can't wait to move out of the area so never have to deal with them.







Another one star review! What a horrible company. 

1. The website. Was down for almost a year and then sporadically works. 
2. You cannot autopay you must send a check
3. Phone service... wait on hold and then listen to this lady prattle on about what the company will not or cannot do in a sing song voice over and over again 
4. Moving out: you have to send them PROOF of moving out or they will send you a bill to your NEW address for your OLD address. Does that make any sense whatsoever???

Terrible company!







Literally everyone I have talked to in customer service here had been rude and short tempered. At one point I was literally told that I had missed my appointment because I wasn't home when I in fact took the whole day off to stay at home just for them. The man whom came out to actually turn on my gas was very pleasant though.







Yelp needs a negative star rating... 

Washington Gas customer support people are utterly useless.  Both from calling their support number and e-mailing customersupport@washgas.com.  Took me over a month to finally resolve a billing issue, where the home builder's bill was on my account.  

Over the course of a month, I spoke with several customer support reps and maybe one or two were truly helpful. E-mailing customersupport@washgas.com is even worse. All they do is copy and paste pre-written bullshit and then write some bullshit saying your clarification request is still being processed. Nothing I received by e-mail was ever helpful. 

So pretty much their customer support is useless, cause they have a back office that actually solves the issues. It would seem like issues get lost in translation from customer support to their back office. 

The problem was that someone on the Wash Gas end screwed up when I called before closing to have the account transfer to my name on my requested effective date, which caused the builder's bill to show up in my account. 

Whatever, finally got it resolved. Try to hire some smarter people for your customer support.







Rating systems need to have negative stars for "messed up" circumstances.

When calling for service you have to wait the entire day because they do not give time windows.  If they don't show up then oh, well try again another day.  They are very good at turning your gas off.  Not so much with getting it turned back on.  Some techs call but most don't.  One showed up about two to three days after I called (at a time when no one would be home).  I am literally at the complaining to third parties stage.  Seriously consider going all electric if you have the funds.  I even received a gas delivery charge when my house currently has no gas for about a month.







I haven't even moved into the apartment that requires a Washington Gas account yet, and I can already see that the next year or more of dealing with this is going to be pure, unmitigated hell.

As everyone else has already said, their website is a complete abomination. It astounds me that this company can provide service to such a large area and have zero regard for the necessity of a functional website. To begin with, it is impossible to create the online profile that is required to set up autopay. You can try, as I did, multiple times on multiple days for multiple weeks, and you will continuously get an error message. I emailed their help desk and their response was essentially, "Yes, sorry about that, we've been having technical difficulties. Bye." I responded with something along the lines of, "Ok so I just... don't make an online profile then?" No response.

That was just the beginning.

We just had service started to this apartment (which we haven't actually moved into yet), so I suspected we would have a service initiation fee of some sort. But, strangely enough, when I checked my balance online, it said $0. When I called and tried to pay my balance through the automated system, it also said it was $0. Since we don't live in the apartment yet, we haven't been getting the mail there, so I can't verify whether or not they sent a paper bill. That shouldn't matter, though, because it's 2017 and every establishment in existence is expected to have some type of virtual payment method that prevents you from having to rely on paper statements and send physical checks.

Once I speak to a human, he confirms that I do indeed owe a $15 fee due in six days. Mhm. I ask him how I am supposed to go about paying that seeing as both the website and automated phone payment system think my balance is $0. After informing me that "The problem is not us, ma'am, the problem is the internet," he redirects me to... the same automated number that won't let me pay because it thinks my account balance is $0. Thanks, man!

So I call again. I speak to a second person and explain the issue I'm having. She casually tells me that it's showing up as a $0 balance because I don't have an actual gas bill added to it yet.

"But the $15 is still due on the 13th... and I have to pay it by the 13th?"

"Yes ma'am."

"Can I go ahead and do that then?"

"Hold on while I redirect you to someone who can help you with that." 

BACK TO THE AUTOMATED PAYMENT LINE. 

I call a third time. I speak to a third person. I explain that this is my third time calling and that I have no way to pay the $15 balance I wouldn't even have known about if I hadn't called to ask. She tries to direct me to the automated payment line again. NOPE. NO. ABSOLUTELY NO. THAT'S NOT WORKING. "I'm sorry for the technical issues, ma'am, and I suggest you try the line again in a few hours." NO. DEFINITELY NOT. Reluctantly, she finally tells me she can accept a check over the phone and takes my bank account/routing numbers, which I'm assuming worked because she gave me a confirmation number (only after having me wait and sharing that she, too, was having "technical difficulties.") 

I'm 90% sure she also called me "dude" at some point during this conversation, but I can only hope I misheard her. 

So we're done now. I'm ready to hang up. I have supposedly (we'll find out) paid my balance. Right before saying goodbye, she chimes to me, "Remember that in the future, you can always review your balance and pay your bill online!"

"Well obviously I can't, because it doesn't work-"

"Have a nice day, ma'am, and let me direct you to our quick customer service survey."  

Kill me.







Since no one in customer service seems to be listening to me I have had to go to social media to see if I can get help. I have been waiting over two months to get gas installed in my house. I am converting my oven, water heater and fireplace. I am waiting at my house for the fourth time for someone to install the meter. First and second time no one showed up. Third time they showed up but I need to Airflow to add a piece of equipment. This has been installed so I called and setup an appointment. I called Washington Gas yesterday and got confirmation someone was coming today and I called this morning and they confirmed again. I am now on the phone and have been told that they are not coming. Four days out of work and my window was 7 a.m. to 5 p.m. Now my husband will have to be at the house on Friday from 7 a.m. to 5 p.m. This is ridiculous. If there was another gas company I could use I would be out of here. Someone high up needs to know that there is no communication with customers, customer service, dispatch and contractors. This is only the tip of the iceberg of what I have been through.







Washington Gas turned off the gas to my house because they were fixing a leak in their system at the street. They left a note on the door at 4 am on Thursday 6/29 saying they had turned off the gas. I don't use the door where they left the note, so I saw it Sat morning 7/1 and called to have the gas turned back on, but was told that Washington Gas doesn't work on weekends so it would be Monday at the earliest that they could turn the gas back on. 

Unbelievable. They can't turn the gas on because Washington Gas technicians don't work weekends. I have been paying my bill on time at this address for 31 years. Now I'm stuck with no hot water or gas to cook with for at least the weekend. Terrible customer service. Especially for a utility that the public depends on.







Without question the worst customer service of any utility or customer focused organization that I have ever dealt with.  You cannot talk to anyone who makes a decision or schedules people.  

Having problems with your meter, they tell you to plan to wait all day.

Want a meter moved, they contract that out to someone and do not plan to get it ever scheduled.

Want to talk to a scheduler for either.  They are not available and the customer service line will tell you they are not allowed to talk to them

When they came to move the meter, they told me I needed a new line from the meter to the street.  This is an expense they need to incur, I have never heard back from them.

Without question, the CEO of Washington Gas should be the next CEO of United Airlines, because they would be my all stars for pathetic approaches to customers.







This place would be a negative if yelp allowed it. As is evidenced by the reviews, wash gas should be investigated by the attorney generals of all three jurisdictions







I hardly ever write reviews but was compelled to add my warnings to the many others about Washington Gas.

METICULOUSLY REVIEW YOUR BILLS!  After my first bill their auto-pay system failed to draft my bank account for the second and subsequent bills.  Since I have never experienced issues before in 17 years of using auto-pay for utilities, I didn't look at the bills posted on my Washington Gas account online.  It wasn't until Washington Gas physically mailed me a disconnect warning that I signed into my account to see what was going on and saw that auto-draft was not working.  My mistake for not assuming they might be incompetent.  Then they added a $65 deposit charge to my next bill since my payment had been considered "late" even though the lateness was due to their auto-pay system failure.  Fine, whatever.

Thereafter, I opted out of auto-pay and manually paid each bill online each month.  Interestingly, the first payment manually made online was reflected in the account payment history and the next bill as expected; but subsequent payments for subsequent bills were not credited to the bills even though they are listed in the account payment history.  They took my money but never credited my account. 

I called Customer Service for an explanation; the representative agreed that she saw the payments but I wasn't getting credited in the bills.  She forwarded the matter to the billing department where they should investigate the issue and have a resolution in 14 days.  I asked why doesn't she just transfer me to that department while I was on the phone so we could resolve it immediately and she responded that they have to follow a process, which takes two weeks to complete.  Wow.

I am moving out of the country in about a week so I imagine that it will be a source of unneeded frustration to collect the $65 deposit and get a resolution to their billing issues while I'm overseas.

I'll leave you with one positive; the Customer Service representatives are courteous and professional despite working with a problematic computer system.  When scheduling a stop date for my service, it literally took the representative over five minutes before she could access my account and over 10 minutes more just to setup the stop service date and forwarding address.  They must be using Tandy computers leftover from 1984 with 300 baud modems to connect to the internet!







The worst company in the world. Put it this way, once they make a mistake on their end, all hell breaks lose. You'll find yourself in stressful situations from constant emails and calls that will get you absolutely nowhere. Managers that say they will help, and nothing happens. Lies and deceitful 'back office' that doesn't communicate with one another. Just a complete nightmare.







Common Sense, where are you?  After being told a technician would be here today between 8 a.m and 1 pm, I called WG at 2;30 to ask where they were.  No one has called, no one has come.  I was told by two different "supervisors" that "Our dispatchers have no way of reaching our technicians once they are out in the field."

Seriously?  I asked, "what if there was an emergency and you had to contact them?"  Again, came the response, "Our dispatchers have NO WAY to reach our technicians once they are out in the field."

Please be on the watch for WG Technicians bouncing about in impenetrable bubbles as they float randomly from place to place.  Catch one if you can.







Based on my experience and those of my neighbors in Georgetown,  Washington Gas is not accountable, transparent, or communicative when it comes to repairing gas lines and related infrastructure above and below our streets.







